Step 2: Initialize Your Local Project
Open your terminal (or Git Bash) and navigate to your project folder:

# Navigate to your project
cd path/to/your/project

# Initialize Git in this folder
git init

# Add all your files to the "staging area"
git add .

# Save your changes locally
git commit -m "Initial commit"

#Confirm Identity
git config --global user.email "cbitssdesigner@gmail.com"
git config --global user.name "Sandeep Kumar"

Link Local to GitHub and Upload
On your new GitHub repository page, you will see a section called "…or push an existing repository from the command line". Copy those commands, or use these (replacing the URL with your actual repo link):


# 1. Rename your local branch to 'main'
git branch -M main

# 2. Connect your local folder to GitHub (Replace the URL with YOUR repo URL)
git remote add origin https://github.com/FedCode/SmartNotesAi.git

# 3. Upload (push) your files to GitHub
git push -u origin main


The Standard "Daily" Workflow
Whenever you finish a feature or a bug fix, run these in order:

Stage the changes:

Bash
git add .
(This tells Git to "track" all the files you just modified.)

Save the snapshot:


Bash
git commit -m "Added a login button to frontend"
(Always write a short, descriptive message so you know what you did when you look back later.)

Upload to GitHub:

Bash
git push


Working from your "Other" System
As we discussed earlier, if you move to a different computer to continue working, follow this order:

When you arrive at the other PC: Run git pull first to grab the latest work you pushed from the first PC.

When you finish working on that PC: Run the add, commit, and push steps above.


Pro-Tips for the Future
Check Status: If you aren't sure what files you've changed, type git status. It will show you a list of modified files in red.

Mistakes: If you accidentally commit something you didn't mean to, don't panic! Git keeps a history of everything, so nothing is ever truly lost.

Branching: Eventually, you might want to try "Branching" (creating a copy of the code to test an idea without breaking the main version), but for now, sticking to the main branch is perfect for a solo project.